            "content": "Average Temperatures: Daytime highs 95-110°F, overnight lows 70-80°F, monsoon humidity July-August\n\nHeat Pump Performance: Modern heat pumps operate efficiently up to 115°F, exceeding Tucson's typical summer highs. During peak cooling demand (3-8 PM when temperatures exceed 105°F), your heat pump runs continuously maintaining setpoint temperatures—this is normal and expected. Overnight lows of 70-80°F allow heat pumps to 'catch up' and pre-cool homes before morning temperatures rise. Variable-speed heat pumps truly excel in summer, ramping capacity up during peak heat and reducing output during milder morning/evening hours for maximum efficiency.\n\nOptimization Tips: Set thermostats to 76-78°F during peak hours (12-8 PM) and pre-cool to 74°F during overnight hours (10 PM-8 AM) when electricity rates are lower and outdoor temps are cooler. Use programmable thermostat 'smart recovery' or 'adaptive recovery' features pre-cooling homes before afternoon heat rather than trying to cool down already-hot homes at 3 PM. Close blinds and curtains on south and west windows reducing solar heat gain by 40-60%. Schedule more frequent filter changes monthly during summer when systems run 12-16 hours daily accumulating dust rapidly. Consider our [link:/services/indoor-air-quality-tucson|indoor air quality] upgrades for superior comfort during long cooling cycles.\n\nEnergy Costs: Expect $180-$280/month for peak summer cooling in typical 2,000 sq ft homes with heat pumps versus $220-$340/month with older 13 SEER AC systems, achieving 15-25% cooling cost savings. Homes with 20+ SEER2 heat pumps save even more."
