            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": "Heat Pump Repair vs. Replacement Decision Matrix\n\nSystem Age 0-7 years, minor repair (<$500): REPAIR – System has 8-13 years remaining lifespan; repair restores full function\n\nSystem Age 0-7 years, major repair ($1,500+): REPAIR if under warranty – Manufacturer warranty likely covers expensive components like compressor\n\nSystem Age 8-12 years, minor repair (<$500): REPAIR – Cost-effective; system has 3-7 years remaining life\n\nSystem Age 8-12 years, major repair ($1,500+): REPLACEMENT usually better – Repair costs approach 30-50% of new system; old efficiency wastes energy\n\nSystem Age 13+ years, any repair >$800: REPLACEMENT strongly recommended – Limited remaining lifespan; new system pays for itself through efficiency gains\n\nSystem Age 13+ years, second major repair: REPLACEMENT immediately – Repair-prone pattern indicates cascade failures ahead\n\nMultiple repairs in 24 months totaling >$1,200: REPLACEMENT – Frequent repairs signal systemic deterioration\n\nSystem efficiency <13 SEER and >10 years old: REPLACEMENT – New 20+ SEER2 system saves $600-$1,200 annually on Tucson cooling costs\n\nCompressor failure on system >10 years old: REPLACEMENT – Compressor replacement costs approach new system investment\n\nR-22 refrigerant system with leak: REPLACEMENT – R-22 refrigerant costs $150-$200/lb; recharge costs exceed repair value"
